11.21.24  5:45 am   to clarify an earlier question, my daughter and i have have different thresholds of boredom, likely due to growing up under different circumstances (ie she has much greater access to digital media than i did at her age). how do i teach her the life skill of occupying oneself in the absence of a tv/tablet.

nevermind, i just realized i've done all i can do and she'll have to work it out on her own. and i/other adults will just have to tolerate her complaining for now.

no wait on second (third?) thought, do you have any thoughts on how to respond to "iiiiii'm booooooored"?

      ah yes, then it's your job to entertain her. like a friend, basically. this is something you should have some special knowledge about, based on your memories of how you and your friends used to entertain each other in the good old days. Now that i think about it, perhaps a good starting point would be to complain to her that in fact you are bored also. make it into a competition. discovering fun in the world is a crazy adventure, and you both need this, so you might as well do it together
